# Dynamic Image Endpoints

> **Thesis:** Dynamic image endpoints must be (1) pure deterministic
> renderers — same input always produces identical bytes — and (2)
> include a renderer version constant in their ETag hash so visual
> changes invalidate downstream caches on deploy. Without (1), the
> render is slow, untestable, and depends on external runtimes;
> without (2), browser/CDN/conditional-GET caches keep serving the
> old bytes for the full max-age window after every renderer change.
>
> **Refrain:** `Pure function in → deterministic bytes out → version
> the renderer in the ETag`

## When this applies

- OG/social-card preview images (`/api/v1/profiles/:slug/og-image`)
- Badge/credential PNGs
- QR code endpoints with branded chrome
- Invoice/receipt PDF generation
- Any endpoint that returns image bytes computed from request input

Does NOT apply to:

- Static image assets served from `frontend/public/images/` (Vite
  hashes filenames; no dynamic rendering)
- User-uploaded images (no rendering; just storage proxy)
- Avatar/thumbnail resizing (use a dedicated image-proxy library)

## Rule 1: Pure renderer functions

The renderer must be a pure Go function: input struct → `[]byte` PNG
output, no I/O, no network, no browser, no embedded language runtime.

**BAD: Node/browser/screenshot pipeline**

```go
// Spawns headless Chrome, navigates to a route, screenshots the page.
// Adds a second runtime path, multiplies deploy surface area, and
// produces non-deterministic bytes (font hinting, anti-aliasing
// vary between Chrome versions).
func RenderOGImage(profile *Profile) ([]byte, error) {
    return chromiumScreenshot("https://localhost/render-og?slug=" + profile.Slug)
}
```

**GOOD: Pure Go renderer**

```go
// Pure function. No network, no shell-out, no external runtime.
// Same input → same bytes. Testable in 50ms via `go test`.
// Hot-reloadable via Air during iteration.
func RenderProfileOGImage(ctx context.Context, profile *PublicProfile) (*OGImage, error) {
    img := image.NewRGBA(...)
    drawCardSurface(img, ...)
    drawText(img, profile.DisplayName, ...)
    // ... pure draw calls only
    return &OGImage{PNG: bytes, ETag: computeETag(profile)}, nil
}
```

**Why this matters:**

- **Testable.** A pure function takes 50ms to test against fixtures;
  a Chrome screenshot test takes 5-10s minimum and requires the
  browser binary in CI.
- **Deterministic.** Same input always produces the same bytes,
  which means ETag stability (a content hash works) and visual
  regression detection (golden-file tests are stable).
- **Fast.** Go's `image/draw` runs in 50-200ms per render. Chrome
  screenshot is 2-5s.
- **Hot-reloadable.** Air rebuilds the Go binary in seconds; a
  Chrome-based renderer requires container restarts.
- **Cache-stable.** No external network calls means no dependence
  on GCS/S3 availability for the render path.

If pure Go rendering can't hit the visual quality bar (e.g. complex
typography with kerning, multi-line text wrapping with hyphenation,
SVG rendering), prefer adding a tiny library (`oksvg`, `rasterx`,
`golang.org/x/image/font/opentype`) over introducing a second
runtime. Go has good libraries for almost everything image-related.

## Rule 2: Renderer version in the ETag hash

Mix a `<renderer>RendererVersion` constant into the ETag hash so
renderer-only changes invalidate downstream caches even when the
input data is unchanged.

**BAD: ETag computed from input data only**

```go
// Renderer change → bytes change → but ETag stays the same because
// the input is unchanged. Cached clients keep showing the old image
// for the full max-age window (5+ min).
func computeETag(profile *PublicProfile) string {
    h := sha256.New()
    fmt.Fprintf(h, "%s\x00", profile.Slug)
    fmt.Fprintf(h, "%s\x00", profile.DisplayName)
    return `W/"og-` + hex.EncodeToString(h.Sum(nil))[:24] + `"`
}
```

**GOOD: Renderer version mixed into the hash**

```go
// Bump this constant whenever the renderer produces visually
// different bytes for the same input.
const ogRendererVersion = "v1"

func computeETag(profile *PublicProfile) string {
    h := sha256.New()
    fmt.Fprintf(h, "%s\x00", ogRendererVersion)  // FIRST
    fmt.Fprintf(h, "%s\x00", profile.Slug)
    fmt.Fprintf(h, "%s\x00", profile.DisplayName)
    return `W/"og-` + hex.EncodeToString(h.Sum(nil))[:24] + `"`
}
```

**Bump the constant when:** layout, colors, fonts, borders, gradients, or
dimensions change. **Do NOT bump when:** only input data changes, or refactors
that don't change rendered output.

**Lock the contract with a test:**

```go
func TestETag_VersionBumpInvalidatesCache(t *testing.T) {
    profile := &PublicProfile{Slug: "test", DisplayName: "Test"}
    currentETag := computeETag(profile)
    bumpedETag := computeETagWithVersion(profile, "v-test-bump")
    if currentETag == bumpedETag {
        t.Fatal("ETag did not change when renderer version differed")
    }
}
```

## Rule 3: Cache headers per response

Different paths emit different cache headers. **Never use the same
Cache-Control for all responses** — it creates cache oracles for
disabled or missing resources.

| Response | Cache-Control |
|---|---|
| `200 image/png` (success) | `public, max-age=300, stale-while-revalidate=3600` |
| `304 Not Modified` (ETag match) | inherits success headers |
| `404 Not Found` (any miss case) | `no-store` |
| `500 Internal Server Error` | `no-store` |

The miss-case `no-store` is **critical for privacy** when the
endpoint resolves auth/visibility state — a `max-age` 404 would
let an attacker confirm a slug's existence via response time after
the cache expires.

Also set `X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff` on success responses so
clients don't sniff the bytes as something other than PNG.

## Rule 4: Per-request render budget

Image rendering is CPU-bound and unbounded by default. Always wrap the
render in a `context.WithTimeout`.

```go
const RenderBudget = 750 * time.Millisecond

func Handler(c echo.Context) error {
    ctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(c.Request().Context(), RenderBudget)
    defer cancel()
    img, err := RenderImage(ctx, profile)
    // ...
}
```

A render that exceeds the budget returns 500 with `no-store` so a
transient slow render doesn't poison the cache.

## Rule 5: Max encoded bytes ceiling

Define an explicit `MaxBytes` constant and reject renders that
exceed it. Unfurlers have their own caps (Slack/LinkedIn/Twitter ~5MB,
Facebook ~8MB) but you want to fail fast on a runaway render.

```go
const OGImageMaxBytes = 2 * 1024 * 1024  // 2MB

if buf.Len() > OGImageMaxBytes {
    return nil, fmt.Errorf("og image too large: %d bytes", buf.Len())
}
```

